commitResults.messageBody:
Duke can receive commands (e.g. todo, deadline, event, bye, mark, etc.)
and save the tasks in a single session.

However, the tasks are not saved after exiting a session (entering
the command "bye").

Adding this feature allows the user to recall the tasks saved before
the current session, by saving the data into the user's hard disk.

Duke can store the deadline dates as strings for a deadline task.

To make the dates more meaningful, the dates should be stored as dates.

The dates are passed as strings, then it is parsed as date (using
java's LocalDate).

Input from user must be in the format of yyyy-mm-dd. Otherwise, it will
be invalid. Times of the deadline are not yet included in this feature.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix bugs for Level-8 combined with Level-7
commitResults.messageBody:
While getting the data from the saved file, a bug will occur if the
type of task is a deadline. This is because the date format in the
saved file is MM dd yyyy instead of yyyy-mm-dd. This will cause the
constructor of the Deadline class to accept MM dd yyyy instead of
yyyy-mm-dd which will cause an error in the constructor.

To fix the error, we should change the date format in the constructor
that is being used to obtain the data from the saved file.

commitResults.messageTitle: Reconstruct files to make the code more OOP
commitResults.messageBody:
The logic of the application is in the Duke.java file, so this does not
follow the OOP Principles: abstraction, encapsulation, polymorphism,
and inheritance.

To follow those principles, we must make separate files and designate
each class to have a specific function (e.g. Parse -> to parse the
user's commands, Ui -> to deal with user interactions, Command -> to
execute the command that the user enters, etc.)

The new classes made are: Ui, Parse, Storage, TaskList, Command
(abstract class), AddCommand, DeleteCommand, ListCommand, MarkCommand,
UnmarkCommand, ExitCommand, CommandType (enum class)

Each class have different functions and the command types are separated
into different classes so as to make the code clear and provide
encapsulation.

Used the enum class for CommandType because there is a finite number
of commands that a user can enter (which makes it suitable according
to the textbook)

commitResults.messageBody:
Users can add, delete, mark, etc. the current tasks.

However, if there are too many tasks, the user will not be able to
find the task that they are searching for.

The find feature allows the user to search for keywords and obtain the
tasks which have the keyword in their description.

This is done by adding find command (class FindCommand) and filter
method in the TaskList class in order to obtain the TaskList that has
been filtered by the keyword.

To ease users in viewing the chat with Kuromi, a GUI is added.

GUI is added using JavaFX (FXML)

Kuromi is able to add, delete, get data from storage.

However, there are invariants that should be followed by the
application.

To check if the application follows the invariants, we can add
assertions to ensure that the app follows the rule (e.g. adding a task
increases the task list size by 1, deleting a task decreases the task
list size by 1, and the task list size of a user obtaining tasks from
the storage is the same as the number of tasks in the storage file.

commitResults.messageTitle: Align with the Code Quality guidelines
commitResults.messageBody:
The Parser class contains only one method (parse) that contains the
processes to split the input into description, deadline, etc. for
each command.

This makes the method to be too long (more than 30 lines).

Therefore, I made a method for each command to separate the processes.
The event command might be still too long (around 40 lines), I didn't
find a way to shorten the number of lines for the method.

Furthermore, I changed the execute method for every child classes of
Command class, so that it aligns with SLAP. I also changed the code
in parser method to align with SLAP

Tweak the GUI to match the asymmetric nature of the conversation: As
the conversation is between the user and the app (not between two
humans), it is asymmetric in nature. Accordingly, it makes sense not to
display both sides of the conversion in the same visual format.

Tweak padding, fonts, colors, alignments to make the GUI more pleasing
to look at.

appropriately as the Window changes size.
